## Redeem Time and Better Yourself

- Time management is very key for one to be productive. I know you probably know that already, however, does your plan start and end only with work? and how do you manage your day so that you don't have more work than time at the end of the day.

- As you progress in life you learn that time management is not just a skill but rather an important aspect of achieving both personal and professional goals.

- Those who value time and aim at redeeming time often get a lot of things done and this is not just about work but general life. The richest people in the world and not by material wealth often start their day early enough say 5 and they often start by exercising then they probably go to work and then later in the day do things that are building them personally or they relax. 

- Unfortunately most of us either overwork and therefore are unable to strike a balance or they underwork and end up procrastinating on tasks. 

## Different techniques of time management 
- There different techniques and insights that have been shared overtime that aim to help one manage their time better. One of those is the 7:8:9 where one spends 7 hours sleeping, 8 working and 9 doing personal activities or relaxing.

- There is also the Pomodoro technique where one works in intervals and takes personal breaks between the work. Say you work for 25 minutes and take 5 minute break to stretch. This method uses a kitchen timer to track the time.

- "Eat that Frog" this is the technique where you start with the most difficult task in the morning then move on to the ones that are less demanding.


## Eisenhower Matrix
- This is a task management technique that involves prioritization of tasks so that no task is left behind and you are able to meet deadlines. 

- The matrix helps organize tasks urgency and important and hence one can remove the things that are not urgent or important. 

- One can come with the matrix by first listing down all they things they need to do in a day or in a particular time frame. 

The matrix allows you choose what to do now, what to do later, what to delegate and what not to do. 

The matrix is shown below:

![][image_ref_bz0gwsmi]

- Quandrant 1: This is where you place the tasks and activities that are both urgenct and important.
- Quadrant 2 : These are tasks are important but not urgent, that means you can push them for later
- Quadrant 3: These are tasks that are not important but urgent like attendinng a meeting. You can delegate that to someone else
- Quadrant 4: Not important and not urgent. These ones you can do away with from the list.

## Five P's of time management
There are Five P's pf time management and they include:

- Prioritize: make a list and Focus on the most important tasks first, and leave less urgent tasks for later. 
- Plan: Create a plan that includes what you need to do, when, and how to do it.This ensures commitment to doing what one needs done.  
- Prepare: Get ready for your tasks by making lists and setting deadlines. 
- Pace: Work in intervals with breaks to help you stay focused and motivated. 
- Persist: Stick to your plan and don't give u

## In conclusion
When one manages there time well, then they are able to not only work and sleep but they can allocate for personal improvement. Prioritization of tasks is a necessity as it helps one keep up with deadlines and also helps you define what you need to do and by when.
In an era where the world has changed and people can work remotely, time management technique is a must have.
